<div class="title">Energy Conservation in Fletcher's Trolley</div>

<p>You can use energy conservation also to calculate the acceleration
of the two blocks.  For this, you need a kinematical relationship
between the acceleration, the displacement, and the change in the
square of the speed of an object.  See Acceleration under Get
Information.</p>

<p><b>Question</b>.  If <i>m<sub>1</sub></i> = 0.6 kg,
<i>m<sub>2</sub></i> = 0.4 kg, and the pulley is massless, what is the
acceleration of the blocks?</p>

<p><b>Answer</b>.  The acceleration has a magnitude of 3.92 m
s<sup>-2</sup>.  You can run the simulation to verify this value.  The
calculation is as follows.</p>

<p>On Page 3, the value of <i>v<sup>2</sup></i> after block 2 has
started from rest and fallen through a displacement <font
face="symbol">D</font><i>y</i> = <i>h<sub>fin</sub></i> -
<i>h<sub>in</sub></i> = 2.5 m was calculated to be
<i>v<sup>2</sup></i> = 19.6 m s<sup>-2</sup>.  The vertical y-axis is
taken to point downwards.</p>

<p>The kinematical relationship referred to above when applied to
block 2 gives</p>

<p align="center"><font face="symbol">D</font><i>v<sup>2</sup></i> =
2 <i>a<sub>y</sub></i> <font face="symbol">D</font><i>y</i> </p>

<p>whence</p>

<p><i>a<sub>y</sub></i> = <font
face="symbol">D</font><i>v<sup>2</sup></i>/(2 <font
face="symbol">D</font><i>y</i>) </p>

<p><spacer type="horizontal" size="15">= (19.6-0)/(2x2.5) = 3.92 m
s<sup>-2</sup>.</p>

<p>You may want to practise calculating the acceleration in a few more
examples, with a different mass for block 2 and different values of
<font face="symbol">D</font><i>y</i>.  You may also want to try it
when the mass of the pulley is non-zero.  You can always check your
answer with the simulation.</p>

<p>You may also want to go back to the expression for
<i>v<sup>2</sup></i> derived on Page 3, generalize it to an expression
for <font face="symbol">D</font><i>v<sup>2</sup></i> in the case that
the initial speed is not zero and then combine it with the kinematical
equation above to obtain the general result</p>

<p><spacer type="horizontal" size="15"><i>a<sub>y</sub></i> =
[<i>m<sub>2</sub></i>/(<i>m<sub>1</sub></i> +
<i>m<sub>2</sub></i>)]<i>g</i>.</p>

<p>Verify that one obtains <i>a<sub>y</sub></i> = 3.92 m
s<sup>-2</sup> when one substitutes the given mass values into this
expression.</p>

<p><b>Comment</b>.  This last equation for <i>a<sub>y</sub></i> does
not require a value for <font face="symbol">D</font><i>y</i>.  <font
face="symbol">D</font><i>y</i> should not be needed because the
acceleration is constant and therefore should depend only on the
constants in the problem, which are the masses and the acceleration
due to gravity.  It should not depend on any variables, like
displacement and speed.</p>

<p><font face="symbol">D</font><i>y</i> <b>was</b> needed in the
calculation at the top of the page because there we started from <font
face="symbol">D</font><i>v<sup>2</sup></i> and the value of <font
face="symbol">D</font><i>v<sup>2</sup></i> is variable and <b>does</b>
depend on the value of <font face="symbol">D</font><i>y</i>.</p>

